Exercises

  1. Create a list with four elements:
    1. the character string "Normal" to represent the distribution
    2. a named vector of the population parameters
    3. a vector of 15 samples from a normal distribution with mean 2 and variance 5
    4. the components of a histogram of these samples
xN_ls <- list(
  distName = "Normal", 
  parameters = c(mean = 2, variance = 5), 
  sample = rnorm(n = 15, mean = 2, sd = sqrt(5))
  )
xN_ls[["histogram"]] <- hist(xN_ls[[3]])

  1. Print the distribution name and parameters (at the same time), and plot the saved histogram.
xN_ls[1:2]
## $distName
## [1] "Normal"
## 
## $parameters
##     mean variance 
##        2        5
plot(xN_ls[[4]])

  1. Print the summary and variance of this sample.
summary(xN_ls[[3]])
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  -0.784   2.853   4.056   3.560   4.892   7.123
var(xN_ls[[3]])
## [1] 5.593057
  1. Test the hypothesis that these observations came from the distribution specified. Store the \(p\)-value, test statistic, critical value, and decision (reject or fail to reject) as new elements of the list.

\(H_0: \mu = \mu_0;\quad H_A: \mu \ne \mu_0.\)

ttest_N <- t.test(
  x = xN_ls$sample,
  alternative = "two.sided",
  mu = xN_ls[[2]][[1]]
)
ttest_N$statistic
##        t 
## 2.554976
ttest_N$p.value
## [1] 0.02289532
critVal_N <- qt(0.975, df = 15 - 1)
abs(ttest_N$statistic) > critVal_N
##    t 
## TRUE
xN_ls$pVal <- ttest_N$p.value
xN_ls$testStat <- ttest_N$statistic
xN_ls$critVal <- critVal_N
xN_ls$decision <- "Fail to Reject the Hypothesis that the True Mean Equals 2"

  1. Repeat this for the rest of the distributions we inspected in Assignment 4. Did you reject the null hypothesis for any of the distributions? If so, which ones. If so, why do you think you rejected the null hypothesis for these distributions? If not, why not?

Students T Distribution:

\(H_0: \mu = \mu_0;\quad H_A: \mu \ne \mu_0.\)

set.seed(1234)
xT_ls <- list(
  distName = "Student's T-distribution", 
  parameters = c(mean = 0, df = 4), 
  sample = rt(n = 15, df = 4)
  )
xT_ls[["histogram"]] <- hist(xT_ls[[3]])

ttest_T <- t.test(
  x = xT_ls$sample,
  alternative = "two.sided",
  mu = xT_ls[[2]][[1]]
)
ttest_T$statistic
##          t 
## -0.5855613
ttest_T$p.value
## [1] 0.5674902
critVal_T <- qt(0.975, df = 15 - 1)
abs(ttest_T$statistic) > critVal_T
##     t 
## FALSE
xT_ls$pVal <- ttest_T$p.value
xT_ls$testStat <- ttest_T$statistic
xT_ls$critVal <- critVal_T
xT_ls$decision <- "Fail to Reject the Hypothesis that the True Mean Equals 2"

Chi-Squared Distribution:

\(H_0: \mu = \mu_0;\quad H_A: \mu \ne \mu_0.\)

set.seed(1234)
xC_ls <- list(
  dist   = "Chi-Squared",
  params = c(df = 2),
  sample = rchisq(n = 15, df = 2)
)
xC_ls[["histogram"]] <- hist(xC_ls[[3]])

hist(xC_ls$sample)

ttest_C <- t.test(
  x = xC_ls$sample,
  alternative = "two.sided",
  mu = xC_ls$params
)
ttest_C$statistic

## -1.554084

F Distribution:

\(H_0: \mu = \mu_0;\quad H_A: \mu \ne \mu_0.\)

set.seed(1234)
xF_ls <- list(
  distName = "F distribution", 
  parameters = c(mean = 1.2, df1 = 90, df2 = 12), 
  sample = rf(n = 15, df1 = 90, df2 = 12)
  )
xF_ls[["histogram"]] <- hist(xF_ls[[3]])

ttest_F <- t.test(
  x = xF_ls$sample,
  alternative = "two.sided",
  mu = xF_ls[[2]][[1]]
)
ttest_F$statistic
##           t 
## -0.09693846
ttest_F$p.value
## [1] 0.9241493
critVal_F <- qt(0.975, df = 15 - 1)
abs(ttest_F$statistic) > critVal_F
##     t 
## FALSE
xF_ls$pVal <- ttest_F$p.value
xF_ls$testStat <- ttest_F$statistic
xF_ls$critVal <- critVal_F
xF_ls$decision <- "Fail to Reject the Hypothesis that the True Mean Equals 1.2"

Poisson Distribution:

\(H_0: \mu = \mu_0;\quad H_A: \mu \ne \mu_0.\)

xP_ls <- list(
  distName = "Poisson distribution", 
  parameters = c(lambda = 3), 
  sample = rpois(n = 15, lambda = 3)
  )
xP_ls[["histogram"]] <- hist(xP_ls[[3]])

ttest_P <- t.test(
  x = xP_ls$sample,
  alternative = "two.sided",
  mu = xP_ls[[2]][[1]]
)
